# Mobile UI Conventions

## 1. Always Use Path Aliases for Imports

Never use relative paths that traverse directories (`../`, `../../`). Use the configured aliases from `tsconfig.json`:

| Alias           | Resolves to         |
| --------------- | ------------------- |
| `@components/*` | `src/components/*`  |
| `@constants/*`  | `src/constants/*`   |
| `@stores/*`     | `src/stores/*`      |
| `@i18n`         | `src/i18n/index.ts` |
| `@i18n/*`       | `src/i18n/*`        |

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
import { Button } from "../../src/components/ui/Button";

// ✅ GOOD
import { Button } from "@components/ui/Button";
```

Same-folder imports (e.g. sibling files) may use `./` relative paths.

## 2. No Inline Styles — Always Use `StyleSheet.create`

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<View style={{ flex: 1, padding: 16 }}>

// ✅ GOOD
const s = StyleSheet.create({ container: { flex: 1, padding: 16 } });
<View style={s.container}>
```

Dynamic styles (e.g. from `pressed` state) are the only exception — keep them minimal.

## 3. Colors Come From `colors` Constant

All colors must come from `mobile/src/constants/colors.ts`. Never use raw hex or rgba strings.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
style={{ color: "#FFFFFF", backgroundColor: "#1B1F2E" }}

// ✅ GOOD
import { colors } from "@constants/colors";
style={{ color: colors.textPrimary, backgroundColor: colors.background }}
```

When adding new colors, add them to `colors.ts` first.

## 4. Never Put `t` in Hook Dependency Arrays

`t` from `useTranslation()` is a stable reference — it does not need to be in deps. If a hook must react to a language change, use `i18n.language` instead.

```tsx
const { t, i18n } = useTranslation();

// ❌ BAD
const sections = useMemo(() => buildSections(t), [t]);

// ✅ GOOD
const sections = useMemo(() => buildSections(t), [i18n.language]);
```

## 5. All User-Visible Text Must Use i18n

Add keys to both `mobile/src/i18n/locales/en.json` and `uk.json`.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<Text>Розпочати</Text>

// ✅ GOOD
<Typography variant="button" i18nKey="onboarding.welcome.getStarted" />
```

## 6. Use `Typography` for All Text

Located at `mobile/src/components/ui/Typography.tsx`.

- `i18nKey` — for translated strings
- `color` — token from `AppColor` (defaults to `textPrimary`)
- `children` — for dynamic/non-translatable content
- Never use raw `<Text>` from `react-native` for user-visible content

### Variants

| Variant       | Use for                         |
| ------------- | ------------------------------- |
| `h1`          | Screen titles                   |
| `h2`          | Section headings                |
| `h3`          | Sub-headings                    |
| `body`        | Default body text               |
| `bodySmall`   | Secondary / supporting text     |
| `label`       | Form labels                     |
| `caption`     | Metadata, timestamps, hints     |
| `button`      | Primary button labels           |
| `buttonSmall` | Secondary / ghost button labels |

```tsx
<Typography variant="h1" i18nKey="onboarding.welcome.title" />
<Typography variant="body" color="textSecondary" i18nKey="onboarding.welcome.subtitle" />
<Typography variant="caption">{transaction.date}</Typography>
```

## 7. Use `Button` for All Tappable Actions

Located at `mobile/src/components/ui/Button.tsx`.

- `variant` — controls appearance
- `size` — `md` (default, 58pt) or `sm` (44pt)
- `i18nKey` — label text (translated)
- `disabled` / `loading` — for state management
- Never build custom `Pressable` + `Text` combos for standard actions

### Variants

| Variant     | Use for                             |
| ----------- | ----------------------------------- |
| `primary`   | Main CTA — accent background        |
| `secondary` | Secondary action — elevated bg      |
| `ghost`     | Subtle action — no background       |
| `outline`   | Bordered action — transparent bg    |
| `danger`    | Destructive action — red background |

```tsx
<Button variant="primary" i18nKey="onboarding.welcome.getStarted" onPress={handleStart} />
<Button variant="ghost" size="sm" i18nKey="onboarding.welcome.login" onPress={handleLogin} />
<Button variant="danger" i18nKey="common.delete" onPress={handleDelete} disabled={loading} />
```

## 8. Reuse Existing UI Components

Before building a new component or screen, check `mobile/src/components/ui/` for existing primitives:

- **`Typography`** — all text
- **`Button`** — all tappable actions
- **`Dropdown`** — selector rows that open a picker
- **`SearchBar`** — search input with search + clear icons
- **`SegmentedControl`** — pill-shaped tab switcher

Compose screens from these building blocks. Only create a new component if no existing one fits.

### `SearchBar` usage

```tsx
import { SearchBar } from "@components/ui/SearchBar";

// Standard usage
<SearchBar
  value={query}
  onChangeText={setQuery}
  placeholder={t("common.search")}
/>;

// Inside a bottom sheet — pass BottomSheetTextInput so focus works correctly
import { BottomSheetTextInput } from "@gorhom/bottom-sheet";

<SearchBar
  value={query}
  onChangeText={setQuery}
  placeholder={t("common.search")}
  InputComponent={BottomSheetTextInput}
  onCancel={() => setQuery("")} // shows "Cancel" button while typing
/>;
```

### `SegmentedControl` usage

```tsx
import { SegmentedControl, Segment } from "@components/ui/SegmentedControl";

type Tab = "expense" | "income";

const segments: Segment<Tab>[] = [
  { key: "expense", label: "Expenses" },
  { key: "income", label: "Income" },
];

<SegmentedControl
  segments={segments}
  activeKey={activeTab}
  onPress={setActiveTab}
  style={{ marginHorizontal: 24 }} // optional outer margin
/>;
```

- `segments` — array of `{ key, label }` objects
- `activeKey` — the currently selected key
- `onPress` — called with the selected key
- Generic `<T extends string>` — keys are type-safe when you provide a union type

## 9. Always Use `@expo/vector-icons` for Icons

Never use emoji or custom SVG components for icons. Always import from `@expo/vector-icons`.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<Typography variant="body">🔍</Typography>
<Text>✓</Text>

// ✅ GOOD
import { Ionicons } from "@expo/vector-icons";

<Ionicons name="search" size={18} color={colors.textTertiary} />
<Ionicons name="checkmark" size={18} color={colors.accent} />
```

Prefer `Ionicons` as the default icon set. Use `size` and `color` directly on the icon — never wrap in `Typography`.

## 10. Form Validation With Formik + Yup

Use `formik` for form state management and `yup` for validation schemas. All validation error messages must use i18n keys.

### Setup pattern

```tsx
import { useFormik } from "formik";
import * as Yup from "yup";

const validationSchema = Yup.object({
  name: Yup.string()
    .trim()
    .required(t("scope.errors.nameRequired"))
    .min(3, t("scope.errors.nameMin", { min: 3 })),
});

const formik = useFormik({
  initialValues: { name: "" },
  validationSchema,
  validateOnChange: false,
  validateOnBlur: false,
  onSubmit: (values) => { /* save logic */ },
});
```

### Key conventions

- **`validateOnChange: false`** and **`validateOnBlur: false`** — only validate on submit so errors don't appear while the user is still typing.
- **Show errors after first submit** — use `formik.submitCount > 0 && formik.errors.field` to derive the error string.
- **Clear error on type** — when the user starts editing a field with an error, clear it immediately:
  ```tsx
  onChangeText={(text) => {
    formik.setFieldValue("name", text);
    if (nameError) formik.setFieldError("name", undefined);
  }}
  ```
- **Error UI** — show error text below the input using `<Typography variant="caption" color="error">`. Keep the input's default styling unchanged — no red borders or background tints.
- **Error messages** — always use translated strings from i18n, never hardcode English text in the schema.

### Error display

```tsx
<View style={s.nameInputContainer}>
  <TextInput ... />
</View>
{nameError && (
  <Typography variant="caption" color="error" style={s.errorText}>
    {nameError}
  </Typography>
)}
```
